<font color="#FF0000">A SLAP IN THE FACE'</font><br>
<tt>Sun Nov 16 15:43:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Enlisted men call Lister's remarks 'a slap in the face'<br><br>
--------------------<br>
By Brett Marcy<br>
THE WASHINGTON TIMES<br>
--------------------<br>
arines at the barracks in Southeast Washington are bristling over assertions by Sara E. Lister, the Army's top civilian personnel official, that the Marine Corps is &quot;extremist,&quot; &quot;dangerous&quot; and out of touch with regular folks. <br>
. . . . &quot;This is a slap in the face to Marines who have worn the uniform for the past 222 years,&quot; 1st Sgt. D.C. Phillips says. &quot;She owes the Marine Corps an apology.&quot;<br>
. . . . &quot;I think it's appalling,&quot; Lance Cpl. Jason Rocco says. &quot;I've poured a lot of guts and sweat to earn this uniform. It's not given to you until the day you graduate. She didn't go through our boot camp.&quot;<br>
. . . . Gunnery Sgt. Randy Matthews says Mrs. Lister may well be the only one to believe Marines are &quot;unconnected to society.&quot;<br>
. . . . &quot;She seems to be the extremist, not the Marines,&quot; Sgt. Matthews says. &quot;She's another civilian with no military experience acting like she's the expert, and she's not.&quot;<br>
. . . . Mrs. Lister's tape-recorded remarks, part of an address to academics and military personnel at an Oct. 26 conference in Baltimore, were made public in Thursday's editions of The Washington Times.<br>
. . . . &quot;I think the Army is much more connected to society than the Marines are,&quot; Mrs. Lister said. &quot;The Marines are extremists. Wherever you have extremists, you've got some risks of total disconnection with society. And that's a little dangerous.&quot;<br>
. . . . She also mocked the Marine Corps uniform, saying &quot;they have all these checkerboard fancy uniforms and stuff&quot; compared with the Army uniform, which is &quot;sort of muddy boots on the ground.&quot;<br>
. . . . Marines gathered in a hall near Sgt. Matthews' office Thursday were especially angry that Mrs. Lister overlooked the many community service projects that Marines perform in addition to their first and foremost duty, being ready to fight when called.<br>
. . . . &quot;We sent Marines over to the [D.C.] elementary schools when they were closed to help fix them up,&quot; Cpl. Rocco says, explaining how Marines painted hallways and classrooms and cleaned up the grounds.<br>
. . . . &quot;We spent a week with gardening tools at this school, cleaning up trash and picking up needles,&quot; Cpl. Joseph Hall says.<br>
. . . . Marines at the Southeast barracks also clean the surrounding streets every morning, something the city government can't be relied on to do.<br>
. . . . &quot;We have community cleanups on a regular basis,&quot; Lance Cpl. James Binkley says.<br>
. . . . Sgt. Matthews says competitive rivalries among the Army, Navy, Air Force and Marines are nothing new, but the services have achieved a healthy working relationship, now endangered by Mrs. Lister's remarks.<br>
. . . . Sgt. Patrick Franklin has an unusual outlook. He served in the Army before he joined the Marines.<br>
. . . . &quot;Each service has just as much pride in what they do as the other services,&quot; Sgt. Franklin says. &quot;To cast aspersions on the honor of either service's men and women is unprofessional and I think it was uncalled for.&quot;<br>
. . . . Mrs. Lister apologized to the Marines Corps on Thursday, but her chances for promotion may have been damaged. She had been mentioned as a candidate to replace Army Secretary Togo West if Mr. West is named to head the Department of Veterans Affairs.<br><br>
